content:
When impatience arises in my mind, or when I feel lazy or afraid;
When I'm inclined toward impulsive behavior or meaningless chatter;
When attachment to my own side emerges in my thoughts—
At such times, I should remain still like a log.

All sentient beings possess the aspect of Buddha-dharma that can be accomplished;
Therefore, in this respect, they are considered equal to the Victorious Ones.
Yet none can equal the Buddhas with their limitless oceans of qualities.

Towards those superior to oneself, jealousy arises;
With equals, one engages in rivalry and competition;
Towards those below, one displays pride; when praised, one becomes arrogant;
When faced with criticism, anger immediately flares up.
When will one ever derive benefit from associating with childish people?

I am without merit and greatly impoverished;
I possess nothing else whatsoever for offerings;
Therefore, O compassionate protectors, who think only of others' welfare;
Please accept these through your miraculous powers, for my benefit.

I offer myself completely to the Victorious Ones and to all their spiritual heirs;
Throughout all lifetimes, I permanently surrender my entire being, relinquishing all self-clinging.
O Supreme Bodhisattvas, please accept me fully as your own;
With reverence, I become your servant to benefit all beings and transcend my negative actions.

Enemies shall cease to exist;
Dear ones too shall be no more;
I myself shall likewise perish;
Thus everything shall come to nothing.

Never drop chairs and other objects with noise carelessly;
Do not forcefully open doors with a slam;
Always delight in humble, stealthy conduct.

Therefore, when one thinks 'I am being praised,'
Joy arises within oneself;
Yet this too is baseless—mere sound without substance;
It is nothing but childish behavior, binding one to cyclic suffering.

Praise and such things cause me to become distracted;
They destroy any disillusionment with saṃsāra I might have;
They breed jealousy toward those endowed with good qualities;
They destroy all excellence and prosperity.

That comes from pleasing sentient beings through patient care and benefit;
Let alone future Buddhahood, why do you not see even in this very life
The prosperity that becomes a foundation for qualities, fame that spreads widely, and happiness arising from benefiting all?

Like one who carries a vessel filled with mustard oil;
Watched by men with drawn swords standing nearby;
Who proceeds with intense focus, fearing death should it spill;
So should the disciplined practitioner.

That one is honored, not I;
That one has gained, while I have not;
That one is praised, while I am criticized;
That one is happy, while I suffer.

That former time when you destroyed me has passed;
That former era was different;
I see where you are going;
I shall demolish all your pride.

If Mahāyāna is rejected for being disputed,
Then abandon āgamas too—for tīrthikas dispute them;
Just as your own and others' Śrāvaka schools contest each others' scriptural traditions.

I am not teeth, hair, or nails;
I am not bones, nor am I blood;
I am not mucus, nor phlegm;
I am not lymph nor pus.

I am not fat nor dust;
The lungs and liver are not me;
Other internal organs are not me either;
I am not excrement or urine;

Just as a banana tree's trunk, when separated into parts, no essence can be found;
Similarly, when sought through analytical examination;
Of past, present, and future consciousness, the self proves not truly existent.

All beings and existences are like dreams in nature;
When analytically examined, they resemble plantain trees;
Between nirvana and samsara,
In ultimate reality, there exists no difference whatsoever.
